### Example 3.7: Visualizing the 3× Table (Three Rows, Growing)

Let's *see* the 3× table, one rectangle at a time.

<!-- BUILD: Renders a sequence of 10 small arrays, each 3 rows tall, width growing from 1 to 10. Arrange in two rows of five. Label each with \"3 × k\". -->

```scheme
(define (draw-times-table-grid n limit)
  ;; Draw n × 1, n × 2, ... n × limit as small grids
  (let* ((dot-spacing 10)
         (dot-radius 3)
         (grid-spacing 48)
         (grids-per-row 5))
    (plot/with
      (list (cons 'title (string-append (number->string n) \"× table\")))
      (apply append
        (map (lambda (k)
               (let* ((row-idx (quotient (- k 1) grids-per-row))
                      (col-idx (modulo (- k 1) grids-per-row))
                      (base-x (+ 24 (* col-idx grid-spacing)))
                      (base-y (+ 24 (* row-idx grid-spacing))))
                 (plot/scatter
                   (apply append
                     (map (lambda (r)
                            (map (lambda (c)
                                   (list (+ base-x (* c dot-spacing))
                                         (+ base-y (* r dot-spacing))))
                                 (range 0 k)))
                          (range 0 n)))
                   (list (cons 'color \"purple\") (cons 'size dot-radius)))))
             (range 1 (+ limit 1)))))))

(draw-times-table-grid 3 10)
```

[VISUAL: Ten small dot grids arranged in two rows of five. Each grid is 3 rows tall. The first is 3 × 1 (3 dots), the second is 3 × 2 (6 dots), up to the tenth which is 3 × 10 (30 dots). Each labeled with its product.]

Each rectangle is three rows tall, and gets one column wider. 3, 6, 9, 12, 15, 18, 21, 24, 27, 30. The 3× table, painted.

