### Example 3.9: Multiplying by 1 (the Identity)

What happens when you multiply by 1?

<!-- BUILD: Prints 1 × k for k from 1 to 10. -->

```scheme
(define (times-table n limit)
  (map (lambda (k)
         (let ((product (* n k)))
           (display (string-append 
                      (number->string n) \" × \" 
                      (number->string k) \" = \" 
                      (number->string product)))
           (newline)
           product))
       (range 1 (+ limit 1))))

(times-table 1 10)
```

[VISUAL: A printed table:
```
1 × 1 = 1
1 × 2 = 2
1 × 3 = 3
1 × 4 = 4
1 × 5 = 5
1 × 6 = 6
1 × 7 = 7
1 × 8 = 8
1 × 9 = 9
1 × 10 = 10
```
]

Multiplying by 1 leaves the number unchanged. We say **1 is the multiplicative identity**. 1 × a = a for any number a.

