### Example 3.11: The Full 10 × 10 Times Table (the Grid)

Let's see the whole times table at once, from 1 × 1 to 10 × 10, as a grid of numbers.

<!-- BUILD: Prints a 10 × 10 multiplication grid, rows and columns labeled 1-10, each cell showing the product. Formatted as a table. -->

```scheme
(define (print-times-table-grid n)
  ;; Print an n × n times table grid
  (display \"    \")
  (map (lambda (col)
         (display (string-append 
                    (if (< col 10) \"  \" \" \")
                    (number->string col) \" \")))
       (range 1 (+ n 1)))
  (newline)
  (display \"   \")
  (map (lambda (col) (display \"----\"))
       (range 1 (+ n 1)))
  (newline)
  (map (lambda (row)
         (display (string-append 
                    (if (< row 10) \" \" \"\")
                    (number->string row) \" |\"))
         (map (lambda (col)
                (let ((product (* row col)))
                  (display (string-append 
                             (if (< product 10) \"  \" 
                                 (if (< product 100) \" \" \"\"))
                             (number->string product) \" \"))))
              (range 1 (+ n 1)))
         (newline))
       (range 1 (+ n 1))))

(print-times-table-grid 10)
```

[VISUAL: A printed 10 × 10 grid, rows labeled 1-10 down the left, columns labeled 1-10 across the top. Each cell shows the product. E.g., row 7, column 8 shows 56.]

This is the heart of multiplication: the times table. Every cell is a product. Row 6, column 7 is 6 × 7 = 42. Notice the diagonal from top-left to bottom-right: 1, 4, 9, 16, 25, 36, 49, 64, 81, 100 — the *squares* (a number times itself).

