### Example 3.14: Patterns in the 9× Table (Digits Sum to 9)

The 9× table has a beautiful pattern: the digits of each product sum to 9.

<!-- BUILD: Prints the 9× table from 9 × 1 to 9 × 10, and for each product, shows the sum of its digits. -->

```scheme
(define (digit-sum n)
  ;; Sum the digits of n
  (if (< n 10)
      n
      (+ (modulo n 10) (digit-sum (quotient n 10)))))

(map (lambda (k)
       (let* ((product (* 9 k))
              (dsum (digit-sum product)))
         (display (string-append 
                    \"9 × \" (number->string k) \" = \" 
                    (number->string product) 
                    \"  (digits sum to \" (number->string dsum) \")\"))
         (newline)
         product))
     (range 1 11))
```

[VISUAL: A printed table:
```
9 × 1 = 9  (digits sum to 9)
9 × 2 = 18  (digits sum to 9)
9 × 3 = 27  (digits sum to 9)
9 × 4 = 36  (digits sum to 9)
9 × 5 = 45  (digits sum to 9)
9 × 6 = 54  (digits sum to 9)
9 × 7 = 63  (digits sum to 9)
9 × 8 = 72  (digits sum to 9)
9 × 9 = 81  (digits sum to 9)
9 × 10 = 90  (digits sum to 9)
```
]

Every product's digits sum to 9. (1+8=9, 2+7=9, 3+6=9, and so on.) A little magic in the times table.

