### Example 3.28: Counting Rows (Add Row by Row)

We can count the area by adding each row. A 5 × 4 rectangle has 4 rows of 5 squares each.

<!-- BUILD: Renders a 5 × 4 grid, with each row colored differently. Print the sum: 5 + 5 + 5 + 5 = 20. -->

```scheme
(define (draw-grid-by-rows cols rows)
  (let* ((cell-size 14)
         (start-x (- 128 (quotient (* cols cell-size) 2)))
         (start-y (- 96 (quotient (* rows cell-size) 2)))
         (colors (list \"red\" \"green\" \"blue\" \"orange\")))
    (plot/with
      (list (cons 'title (string-append 
                           (apply string-append 
                                  (map (lambda (k) 
                                         (string-append 
                                           (number->string cols) 
                                           (if (< k (- rows 1)) \" + \" \"\")))
                                       (range 0 rows)))
                           \" = \" (number->string (* cols rows)))))
      (apply append
        (map (lambda (r)
               (let ((color (list-ref colors (modulo r (length colors)))))
                 (map (lambda (c)
                        (let ((x (+ start-x (* c cell-size)))
                              (y (+ start-y (* r cell-size))))
                          (plot/line
                            (list (list x y) (list (+ x cell-size) y) 
                                  (list (+ x cell-size) (+ y cell-size)) 
                                  (list x (+ y cell-size)) (list x y))
                            (list (cons 'color color) (cons 'width 2)))))
                      (range 0 cols))))
             (range 0 rows))))))

(draw-grid-by-rows 5 4)
```

[VISUAL: A 5 × 4 grid, each row colored differently (red, green, blue, orange). Label \"5 + 5 + 5 + 5 = 20\".]

Four rows of five. Add them: 5 + 5 + 5 + 5 = 20. Same as 5 × 4.

---

### Example 3.29: Counting Columns (Add Column by Column)

Or we can count by columns. Same rectangle, different grouping.

<!-- BUILD: Renders a 5 × 4 grid, with each column colored differently. Print the sum: 4 + 4 + 4 + 4 + 4 = 20. -->

```scheme
(define (draw-grid-by-cols cols rows)
  (let* ((cell-size 14)
         (start-x (- 128 (quotient (* cols cell-size) 2)))
         (start-y (- 96 (quotient (* rows cell-size) 2)))
         (colors (list \"red\" \"green\" \"blue\" \"orange\" \"purple\")))
    (plot/with
      (list (cons 'title (string-append 
                           (apply string-append 
                                  (map (lambda (k) 
                                         (string-append 
                                           (number->string rows) 
                                           (if (< k (- cols 1)) \" + \" \"\")))
                                       (range 0 cols)))
                           \" = \" (number->string (* cols rows)))))
      (apply append
        (map (lambda (c)
               (let ((color (list-ref colors (modulo c (length colors)))))
                 (map (lambda (r)
                        (let ((x (+ start-x (* c cell-size)))
                              (y (+ start-y (* r cell-size))))
                          (plot/line
                            (list (list x y) (list (+ x cell-size) y) 
                                  (list (+ x cell-size) (+ y cell-size)) 
                                  (list x (+ y cell-size)) (list x y))
                            (list (cons 'color color) (cons 'width 2)))))
                      (range 0 rows))))
             (range 0 cols))))))

(draw-grid-by-cols 5 4)
```

[VISUAL: A 5 × 4 grid, each column colored differently. Label \"4 + 4 + 4 + 4 + 4 = 20\".]

Five columns of four. Add them: 4 + 4 + 4 + 4 + 4 = 20. Same total. Rows × columns = columns × rows.

---

### Example 3.30: A Square (Same Width and Height)

A special rectangle: all sides equal. A 5 by 5 square.

<!-- BUILD: Renders a 5 × 5 grid, label \"Area = 5 × 5 = 25 square units (a square)\". -->

```scheme
(define (draw-grid-rectangle cols rows)
  (let* ((cell-size 14)
         (start-x (- 128 (quotient (* cols cell-size) 2)))
         (start-y (- 96 (quotient (* rows cell-size) 2))))
    (plot/with
      (list (cons 'title (string-append 
                           \"Area = \" (number->string cols) \" × \" 
                           (number->string rows) \" = \" 
                           (number->string (* cols rows)) 
                           \" square units\" 
                           (if (= cols rows) \" (a square)\" \"\"))))
      (apply append
        (map (lambda (r)
               (map (lambda (c)
                      (let ((x (+ start-x (* c cell-size)))
                            (y (+ start-y (* r cell-size))))
                        (plot/line
                          (list (list x y) (list (+ x cell-size) y) 
                                (list (+ x cell-size) (+ y cell-size)) 
                                (list x (+ y cell-size)) (list x y))
                          (list (cons 'color \"blue\") (cons 'width 1)))))
                    (range 0 cols)))
             (range 0 rows))))))

(draw-grid-rectangle 5 5)
```

[VISUAL: A 5 × 5 grid of blue outlined squares. Label \"Area = 5 × 5 = 25 square units (a square)\".]

When the width and height are the same, it's a *square*. Area = 5 × 5 = 25. A number times itself is called a *perfect square*.

